Here's the build map. The key structure: your four extensions split cleanly into two phases joined by the single patch, and two of them are *tooling* that gates the others rather than shipping in the bot itself.Walking the four, in dependency order rather than the order you listed them:

**Adversarial bot panel — build first, because it's the instrument everything else is measured on.** This isn't part of the bot; it's the test rig, and until it exists you're flying blind (which is what made V5's failures invisible). Anchor it on the five known reference strategies, then add the *punishers* that the references don't cover: a trap-TAG that slow-plays monsters and check-raises your c-bets, a sticky calling-station that taxes every bluff, a perma-jammer, a nit, a loose-aggressive maniac, a pure pot-odds caller, and — the one most people skip — a counter-exploiter that watches your aggression frequency and starts trapping it. Vary stack depths. Then bolt on the discipline from before: a fire-rate counter per gate, a cross-field grid (every candidate scored on *all* sub-fields plus net), and a train/validate split so a change that only helps the bots you tuned against gets caught. A reactive dial that stays net-positive against a panel built to punish aggression is one you can trust on 1 June.

**Reactive dial — highest EV, and the thing that closes your known leak.** This is the reactive-not-predictive layer you asked about, and yes, it should be the default: a continuous λ-weighted nudge to your existing thresholds keyed on *observed* field passivity (the medium-bucket fold rate across live opponents you already track), touching the common spots — in-position flop c-bet frequency, late-position open width, light 3-bets and limp-attacks versus folders, thinner value. It self-tunes to whoever sits down, so it can't be wrong about an opponent it hasn't met. This is what should turn that 45.6% tight-field win rate into something comfortably positive. Validate it on the panel, ship it for D1 only if the grid says net-positive.

**GTO preflop extension — raises the floor everywhere, bigger lift.** Replace v4.1's coarse `_preflop_class` buckets and tight `open_floor` with proper position-aware 6-max ranges: opens per seat, a 3-bet/4-bet structure, and a vs-open response matrix. Derive from public 6-max charts or a light offline solve; it ships as a tiny lookup. The honest caveat — pure GTO preflop is *unexploitative*, so it won't by itself beat the folders (they don't punish you preflop), but it plugs leaks against the strong/adaptive opponents and gives the reactive dial a sane baseline to deviate *from*. Realistically this is the most work of the three, so start it now but **don't block your D1 submission on it** — if it isn't proven by the 31st, it's a prime patch-window candidate.

**Backtester + predictive layer — post-D1, and the backtester you can mostly build now.** The backtester ingests the D1 hand-history JSON, replays it, and emits per-opponent stat profiles plus a ranking of who's actually exploitable and how. You've already written the hard part — `_reconstruct_hand` is your replay engine; point it at saved JSON instead of live state. Build it this week so it's ready the moment data lands. The *predictive* exploit layer (the V5-style "this specific villain overfolds to turn barrels → barrel it") is the only piece that genuinely waits, and now it's grounded in real observed opponents instead of archetypes you imagined — which is exactly why it'll work this time. It fits into your single finals patch.

